 COLOMBO, Sept 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Sri Lanka leg spinner Upul Chandana has announced his retirement from international cricket, accusing selectors of treating him unfairly and claiming their politics had forced him to reconsider his future. "I have not been considered even for a place in the Hong Kong Sixes side which goes to prove that the selectors don't want me in the national side," an emotional Chandana said at a news conference on Wednesday. According to Sri Lanka cricket sources, Chandana is close to signing a contract with the rebel Indian Cricket League (ICL), a Twenty20 team competition starting next month. "My performances back my credentials, I am still physically fit and have no injuries -- I still have plenty of cricket left in me," the 35-year-old added. "But if I am not going to be selected to play again for my country I have to look at my future and, after talking to my wife and a few other close friends, I decided the best solution was to concentrate my energies elsewhere." The leg spinner played 16 tests and 147 one-day internationals since making his debut in 199
